. ( ) . . ( stopping words .) 

listOfCodes = c(580, 730, 967, 700, 917, 968, 821, 766, 1023, 786, 963, 98, 1400, 883, 564)
listOfBooks = c("The Pickwick Papers", "Oliver Twist", "Nicholas Nickleby", "The Old Curiosity Shop",
                "Barnaby Rudge", "Martin Chuzzlewit", "Dombey and Son", "David Copperfield", 
                "Bleak House", "Hard Times", "Little Dorrit", "A Tale of Two Cities",
                "Great Expectations", "Our Mutual Friend", "The Mystery of Edwin Drood")
books = list()
listWord = list()
for(i in 1:length(listOfCodes)){
    books[[i]] = gutenberg_download(listOfCodes[i])
    }
for(i in 1:length(listOfCodes)){
    dick = books[[i]]
    dick %>% str_replace_all("\"", "") -> dick
    dick %>% str_replace_all("[[:punct:]]","") %>% str_split(pattern = "\\s") %>% unlist() %>% table() %>% as.data.frame(stringsAsFactors = F) -> dick
    colnames(dick) = c("word","count")
    dick %>%
        filter(!str_to_lower(word) %in% stop_words$word) %>% 
        filter(str_length(word)>1) %>% 
        filter(!str_detect(word,"\\d")) %>%
        arrange(desc(count)) -> dick
    dick %>% mutate(proper = !word %in% str_to_lower(word)) -> dick
    listWord[[i]] = dick
}

stat = bind_rows(listWord)
stat %>% mutate(word = str_to_lower(word)) %>% filter(word != "dont") %>%  group_by(word) %>% summarise(count = sum(count)) %>% arrange(desc(count)) -> stat
top20 = stat %>% head(20)
hchart(top20, hcaes(x = word, y=count), type = 'bar') %>% 
    hc_yAxis(title = list(text = 'Number of occurance')) %>% 
    hc_xAxis(title = list(text = 'Word'))

story = listWord[[5]]
story %>% mutate(word = str_to_lower(word)) %>% group_by(word) %>% summarise(count = sum(count)) -> story
story %>% filter(word %in% sentiments$word) %>% full_join(sentiments %>% select(word, sentiment)) %>% na.omit() -> state
## Joining, by = "word"
state %>% filter(sentiment == "positive" | sentiment == "negative") %>% unique(by='word') -> state
state %>% group_by(sentiment) %>% arrange(desc(count)) %>% slice(1:20) -> stateTops
hchart(stateTops, type = 'column', hcaes(x = sentiment, y = count, group = word))

We will use a hypothesis test to determine stronger sentiment 

t.test(state$count[which(state$sentiment=="negative")], state$count[which(state$sentiment=="positive")], alternative = 'less')
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  state$count[which(state$sentiment == "negative")] and state$count[which(state$sentiment == "positive")]
## t = -3.7964, df = 2881.3, p-value = 7.492e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##       -Inf -1.263233
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  6.182498  8.412015

We can conclude that positive words are used more frequently.

    crt = mis %>% filter(section == i)
    crt %>% str_replace_all("\"", "") %>% str_replace_all("[[:punct:]]","") %>% str_split(pattern = "\\s") %>% unlist() %>% table() %>% as.data.frame(stringsAsFactors = F) -> crt
    colnames(crt) = c("word","count")
    crt %>% mutate(word = str_to_lower(word)) %>% group_by(word) %>% summarise(count = sum(count)) -> crt
    crt %>% filter(word %in% sentiments$word) %>% full_join(sentiments %>% select(word, sentiment)) %>% na.omit() %>% 
        filter(sentiment == "positive" | sentiment == "negative") %>% unique(by='word') %>% 
        group_by(sentiment) %>% summarise(count = sum(count)) -> crt
    rep = bind_rows(rep, crt %>% mutate(section = i))
}

hchart(rep, type = 'line', hcaes(x = section, y=rate, group=sentiment))

. . 1-gram, 2-gram . N-gram .

In the code below, a chapter column is added to the data frame, text of book Oliver Twist, then for each chapter, 1-gram and 2-gram is extracted and distribution of 1-gram and 2-gram for different chapters are plotted. 

crt = books[[2]]
crt$chapter = 0
for(i in 1:nrow(crt)){
    row = crt[i,2]
    if(str_detect(row, "^CHAPTER")){
        crt$chapter[i] = 1
    }
}
crt$chapter = cumsum(crt$chapter)
gram1Chap = data.frame()
gram2Chap = data.frame()
for(i in 1:max(crt$chapter)){
    tmp = crt %>% filter(chapter == i)
    gram1 = tokenize_ngrams(tmp$text, n=1, lowercase = T) %>% 
        unlist() %>% table() %>% data.frame(stringsAsFactors = F)
    colnames(gram1) = c("pair", "count")
    gram1 = gram1 %>% arrange(desc(count)) %>% mutate(idx = row_number()) %>% mutate(chapter = i)
    gram1Chap = bind_rows(gram1Chap, gram1)
    gram2 = tokenize_ngrams(tmp$text, n=2, lowercase = T) %>% 
        unlist() %>% table() %>% data.frame(stringsAsFactors = F)
    colnames(gram2) = c("pair", "count")
    gram2 = gram2 %>% arrange(desc(count)) %>% mutate(idx = row_number()) %>% mutate(chapter = i)
    gram2Chap = bind_rows(gram2Chap, gram2)
}
ggplot(data = gram1Chap, aes(x = idx, y=count, color = chapter)) + 
    geom_point() +
    ggtitle("Oliver Twist 1-gram Distributions") + 
    xlab("Pair Index") + 
    ylab("Number of Occurance")

ggplot(data = gram2Chap, aes(x = idx, y=count, color = chapter)) + 
    geom_point() +
    ggtitle("Oliver Twist 2-gram Distributions") + 
    xlab("Pair Index") + 
    ylab("Number of Occurance")

We can conclude from plots that distribution of 1-grams and 2-grams remain same through out the stroy. In the code below, 1-grams and 2-grams are extracted for each book and then parameters of a fitted distribution are determined and saved to a matrix. 

gram1Co = c()
gram2Co = c()
for (i in 1:15){
    crt = books[[i]]
    gram1 = tokenize_ngrams(crt$text, n=1, lowercase = T) %>% 
        unlist() %>% table() %>% data.frame(stringsAsFactors = F)
    colnames(gram1) = c("pair", "count")
    gram1 = gram1 %>% arrange(desc(count)) %>% mutate(idx = row_number())
    lm = lm(log(count)~log(idx), data = gram1)
    coef1gram = lm$coefficients
    gram2 = tokenize_ngrams(crt$text, n=2, lowercase = T) %>% 
        unlist() %>% table() %>% data.frame(stringsAsFactors = F)
    colnames(gram2) = c("pair", "count")
    gram2 = gram2 %>% arrange(desc(count)) %>% mutate(idx = row_number())
    lm = lm(log(count)~log(idx), data = gram2)
    coef2gram = lm$coefficients
    gram1Co = cbind(gram1Co, coef1gram)
    gram2Co = cbind(gram2Co, coef2gram)
}
gram1Co = data.frame(gram1Co)
colnames(gram1Co) = listOfBooks
gram2Co = data.frame(gram2Co)
colnames(gram2Co) = listOfBooks

Enrest Hemingway novels are not available in gutenberg package so books Anna Karenina, War and Peace, The Cossacks, Ressurection from Leon Tolstoy are going to be analysed. 

tolstBooks = list()
code =c(1399, 2600, 4761, 1938)
bookNames = c("Anna Karenina", "War and Peace", "The Cossacks", "Resurrection")
for(i in 1:length(code)){
    tolstBooks[[i]] = gutenberg_download(code[i])
}
gram1Co = c() 
gram2Co = c()
for (i in 1:length(code)){
    crt = tolstBooks[[i]]
    gram1 = tokenize_ngrams(crt$text, n=1, lowercase = T) %>% 
        unlist() %>% table() %>% data.frame(stringsAsFactors = F)
    colnames(gram1) = c("pair", "count")
    gram1 = gram1 %>% arrange(desc(count)) %>% mutate(idx = row_number())
    lm = lm(log(count)~log(idx), data = gram1)
    coef1gram = lm$coefficients
    gram2 = tokenize_ngrams(crt$text, n=2, lowercase = T) %>% 
        unlist() %>% table() %>% data.frame(stringsAsFactors = F)
    colnames(gram2) = c("pair", "count")
    gram2 = gram2 %>% arrange(desc(count)) %>% mutate(idx = row_number())
    lm = lm(log(count)~log(idx), data = gram2)
    coef2gram = lm$coefficients
    gram1Co = cbind(gram1Co, coef1gram)
    gram2Co = cbind(gram2Co, coef2gram)
}
gram1Co = data.frame(gram1Co)
colnames(gram1Co) = bookNames
gram2Co = data.frame(gram2Co)
colnames(gram2Co) = bookNames
